{
  "doc_id": "40682",
  "text": "The Fabaceae family is the second largest family of medicinal plants being used as traditional medicine [CITATION_1] . Several studies have proven that plants from the Fabaceae family have strong antioxidant potentials [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Antioxidants are microconstituents that inhibit lipid oxidation through prevention of the initiation or propagation of oxidizing chain reactions [CITATION_5] , suppress the formation of reactive oxygen species, and inhibit enzymes or chelate elements involved in free radical production and scavenge reactive species [CITATION_6] . These mechanisms of action are necessary in cell protection, thus contributing to the prevention of cardiovascular diseases, cancer and other chronic diseases [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . The search for natural antioxidant compounds has been intensified in recent years due to the reported data that synthetic antioxidants are dangerous to human health [CITATION_9] . In addition, natural-based compounds are inherently better tolerated by the body than synthetic compounds [CITATION_10] .",
